prompt:
I need a chess move generator I can actually trust, and the only test methodology I believe in for these is perft: walk the game tree to a fixed depth, count the leaf nodes, compare against the published reference counts. Any bug in the rules — a phantom castle, a missed en passant pin, a promotion that forgets the knight — and the numbers drift within a couple of plies. No search, no eval, no engine ambitions: just the complete rules of chess, exact. C++20, stdlib only, chess.h and chess.cpp:

    struct Chess { /* your representation, default-constructible */ };

    bool chess_load(Chess *c, const std::string &fen);
    std::vector<std::string> chess_moves(const Chess *c);
    bool chess_apply(Chess *c, const std::string &uci);
    long long chess_perft(const Chess *c, int depth);

- chess_load parses a full FEN (placement, side to move, castling rights, en passant square, halfmove, fullmove). Return false on anything structurally malformed: wrong field count, not 8 ranks, a rank whose pieces plus digits don't cover exactly 8 files, unknown letters, side that isn't w or b. The fixture FENs are otherwise sensible positions; you don't have to referee semantics beyond that.
- chess_moves returns ALL strictly legal moves (a move may never leave your own king attacked) in coordinate notation, sorted ascending as plain strings: "e2e4", castling as the king's two-square hop "e1g1"/"e1c1", promotions with a lowercase piece suffix "a7a8q"/"a7a8n"/"a7a8r"/"a7a8b".
- chess_apply plays one move if and only if it is in that legal set, returning false and changing nothing otherwise.
- chess_perft counts the move sequences of exactly the given length (a tree walk — transpositions count every time, no dedup, no hashing needed). Depth 0 is 1, negative is 0, and a position with no legal moves has no children.

Full rules means full rules: double pawn pushes setting the en passant square, en passant captures (only against the pawn that just double-pushed, and still subject to the your-king-stays-safe law — the rank-pin case is in the suite), all four promotion pieces on pushes and captures, castling with every classical condition (rights intact, squares between empty, king not in check, king's transit and landing squares unattacked), rights dying when the king moves, when a rook moves, and when a rook is captured on its home square.

test_chess.cpp pins the standard published perft values for six fixture positions — start position to depth 4 plus the usual castle/EP/promotion torture positions — and spot-checks the move lists (sorted order, castling availability, the EP pin, underpromotions). Those counts are exact. make test runs it; test_chess.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile are off limits.
